.TH panPage  22.14 "Fri Oct 06 02:12:27 2023" 
.SH Name \fBpanPage\fR \-  Pans the viewable window in pages defined by the offsets
.SH Syntax \fBpanPage\fR  [-help]  <x> <y> 
.P Pans the viewable window in pages defined by the offsets. The size of each page is equal to the size of the current viewable window. Use this command at any stage of the design flow. 
.SH Parameters    "\fB-help\fR" Prints a brief description that includes type and default information for each panPage parameter.  For a detailed description of the command and all of its parameters, use the man command: man panPage.  "\fB<x y>\fR" Specifies xand y offsets to indicate number of pages to pan. A positive value of <x> specifies a pan of <x> pages to the right. A positive number of <y> specifies a pan of <y> pages toward the top.  You can specify integer values for <x> and <y>. 
.SH Examples
.RS  "*" 2 The following command pans the display to the right by one page   panPage 1 0
.RE
.RS  "*" 2 The following command pans the display to the left by one page   panPage -1 0
.RE 
.SH Related Information
.RS  "*" 2 pan  "*" 2 panCenter  "*" 2 View Menu chapter in the Menu Reference 
.RS  "*" 2 Pan
.RE  "*" 2 The Main Window chapter in the Menu Reference 
.RS  "*" 2 Mouse Operations
.RE 
.RE
